-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Linux Commands ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

-pwd
Print Working Directory display the full path of working Directory

-ls
List folders and files in the current path or directory
-ls [directory path]
list all the folders and files in this path without changing the current directory
-ls -R [directory]
display all the folders and files and the folder contents
-ls -a
show all files and folders include hidden

-cd [dir name]
Change directory
-- cd ..
go up directory

-mkdir [directory name]
make directory

-touch [filename]
create new file 

-rm [filename]
remove file 
-rm -r [dirname]
delete directory and all the file with in

-clear 
clear the terminal

-mv [filename] [new_filename]
Rename the file or direcotry 

-cp -r [dirname] [new_dirname]
copy file or folder from path to other path -r used with direcotries
-cp [filename] [new_filename]


-history
give a list of all past commands typed in the current terminal session

-history 2
display the last 2 commands 


-CTRL + r 
search History



-CTRL + c
stop current command 


-cat [filename]
display the file content


-uname -a
show system and kernel

-lscpu
display cpu info
-lsmem
-display memory info

-sudo
excute command as superuser

-adduser [username]
add new user

-su [-username]
switch users

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Vim Commands -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-vim 
open vim or vi text editor in command mode 
-i 
to switch to insert mode
-esc 
to switch to command mode
-dd 
delete entire line 
-u
undo action
-/pattern 
search file in command mode 
-:%s/old/new 
search and replace old with new in command mode 
-:wq
save and exit in command mode 
-:q!
quite and discard changes in command mode 
-:q
quite in command mode
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Permissions&Owners -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

--- every file and directory has 3 groups Owner(u),Group(g),Others(o) each group has 3 Permissions (Read,Write,Excute)
--- Linux has 3 types of Users (Super Users,Account Users,Services Users mysql,apache ... etc)
-ls -l
print files and folders with its permissions

-chown <username>:<groupname> <filename>
change ownership of the file

-chown <username> <filename>
change only the user for file

-chgrp <groupname> <filename>
change only the group for the file

-chmod -x <file Or direcotry>
remove excution mode from this directory

-chmod g-w <fileOrfolder>
remove write permission fro the group
-chmod g+x <fileOrfolder>
add permission execute for the group

-chmod u+x <fileOrfolder>
give permission to user for execute 

-chmod o+x <fileOrfolder>
give excute permmission for other users and group to excute 

-chmod +x <fileOrfolder>
-chmod a+x <fileOrfolder>
give excute permission for all (a flag stand for all)

-chmod g=rwx <fileOrfolder>
assign the read,write,excute in one line for the group
-chmod g=r-- <fileOrfilder>
set all the 3 permissions 

-chmod 777 <filename>
give permission for every one on system for file or folder

----------------------------------------------------------------------------- Manage Users&Groups -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
--- all users storted in /etc/passwd evey one can read it but only root can change it 

-cat /etc/passwd
--- the output return USERNAME:PASSWORD:UID:GID:GECOS:HOMEDIR:SHELL , the x after username is the encrypted password stored in /etc/shadow 
--- UID,GID the User ID , Primary Group id which stored in /etc/group

-adduser <username>
create new user to the system
-passwd <username>
change the password of the user
-su -  <username>
switch  user , which allow to change user on the command line 
-su - 
will log u as root user
-addgroup <groupname>
this will create new group
-useradd <username>
create new user
-groupadd <groupname>
create new group
-deluser <username>
-userdel <username>
delete user
-groupdel <groupname>
-delgroup <groupname>
delete group


--- adduser,addgroup,delgroup used in terminal ,useradd,gropadd,groupdel low level when excuting in autmated way

-usermode [options]  <username>
change the group of the user
-usermode -g <groupname> <username>
change the user primary group
-usermode -G <group1>,<group2> <username>
add the user to multiple groups which may alter its exiting group set
-usermode -aG <group1>,<group2> <username>
append new groups to current user groups
-groups 
will append the groups which the user belongs to
-groups <username>
display list of  the groups the user belogn to
-useradd -G <group> <username>
this will specify the group the user will join with the default grou
-gpasswd -d <username> <groupname>
remove user from group


---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Pipes -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
--- every output  of linux command can be input for another command

-cat /var/log/syslog | less

the less command taks the out put of the cat command and make the output readable using pages
-ls la /usr/bin | less
print the output in pages

-grep
globally search for reqular expression and print out , search for particular pattern of characters and display all lines that contain that pattern 
-history | grep sudo
grap all sudo command from history command 

-history | grep ls | less
display all uses for ls from history as pages

-history | grep "sudo chomd"

-ls /user/bin | grep java

using grep for search for file or directory or content of the file

-history | grep sudo > sudo-command.txt
redirect the output into file using > sign
-history | grep sudo >> sudo-command.txt
>> is append to the file > replace the content of the file or create it

-clear;sleep 1; echo "hello to devops";
the ; is used to excute command one by one


